[Lecture on 1.1]
Lecture "1.1" refers to week 1, day 1 (i.e. Monday). Similar notation is used throughout

Professor: Mark Flanagan
N.B. Module content has changed since last year, previous exams may not be relevant

Necessary backgrounds:

Signals & System (Fourier, FFT, autocorrelation, PSD, etc.)
Probability Theory (Bayes' rule)
Random Signals (AWGN, etc.)
Linear Algebra (Vector spaces, inner products, etc.)
Preliminary section on DMCs and MAP rule.
Three mains sections:

Signal space analysis
Modulation techniques
Wireless communications
Recommended textbook: "Communication Systems" by Simon Haykin (4th ed)



Idealised channel with no memory.
Symbols can be sent. Symbols can be received. Transmitter must identify sent symbols based on the received symbols.

A matrix maps the probability of each TX symbol being received as each RX symbols
'a priori' probabilities give the probability of being sent in the first place
'a posteriori' probabilities give the probability that was sent based on

Question: Suppose is observed at the output. What is the optimum decision rule?
Answer: Want to be the most likely value could have had based on the observation i.e. we want to choose to maximise . This is called the "maximum a posteriori" (MAP) rule.

[End of lecture on 1.1]
[Lecture on 1.3]

Here the receiver sets its decision to the symbol for which was the most likely to be received, i.e.

Note that MAP and ML are equivalent if the transmission symbols are equiprobable
(because is a constant so the second factor in the equation above becomes irrelevant for argmaxing)
Note: People often misuse the term 'maximum likelihood' to refer to MAP (though this is often irrelevant because values are usually equiprobable)

Say we minimise the probability of making the wrong decision
Probability of being correct:

This yields the MAP rule.

[End of lecture on 1.3]
[Lecture on 1.4]

If the a priori probabilities are unknown, we treat them as variables and consider the worst-case set of a priori probabilities for each possible rule, then select the rule with the lowest worst-case probability of error.
Consider a BSC with 0s and 1s - let the a priori probability of 0 be denoted P(0).
There are four possible decision rules - plot the probability of error for each one as a function of P(0). You'll find it's a set of lines in the box [0,0]-[1,1]
The minimax rule is the one with the lowest maximum.

We represent signals as a linear sum of orthonormal basis functions
Orthonormal => orthognonal and normalised
Orthogonal functions: their correlation (intergral of their product from 0 to T) is zero
Normalised: the energy of each signal is 1 (i.e. its correlation with itself is 1)

Nearest Neighbour Decision Rule

Select the closest one to the received vector as .

In the case that symbols are unequal a priori probabilities, the decision boundaries 'shift around' to make some more likely, according to the decision rule below:


Consider the PSD and autocorrelation of white noise.

In MAP detection, the probability of error depends only on the Euclidian distance between the points and
The additive Gaussian noise vector is a sphere in the signal space
Therefore, rotating of translating the entire constellation through signal space has no bearing on the probability of error

Information Theory COMP 30690

Include explicit instructions (README file) on how to run/compile it
Submit separate files separately, no zip files
The plagiarism detector won't work on zip files (lmao good to know)
Any programming language is fine (he will be using MATLAB)


Introduction and Prerequesites
Review of calculus and algebra
Entropy, mutual information, asymptotic equipartition property...
Data compression
Error detection and correction
Channel capacity

Mainly:

T. Cover & J. Thomas "Elements of Information Theory" (2nd ed.) Wiley & Sons 2006 (Chapters 1,2,3,5,7)
Also:

S. Ross "A First Course on Probability" (10th ed.) Prentice Hall, 2018
D. McKay "Information Theory, Inference, and Learning Algorithms" Cambridge University Press, 2004

Claude Shannon developed the theory of information during WWII (wasn't published till after the war)
Seminal paper: A mathematical theory of communication
According to Shannon
Information Information is the ability to distinguish reliably among possible alternative messages
i.e. one of many possibilities is being encoded
There is a greater than 95% chance of at least 1 bit error occurring in 4 GB of memory in a 72h period at sea level - error detection and correction is important!
Most basic error correction scheme:

Send every symbol three times and take the majority
This is reasonably effective but not at all foolproof, and extremely inefficient
Every noisy channel has a 'capacity' (C) which defines the limit on the 'rate' of code (i.e. the ratio of original message to encoded message)
(C is dimensionless, not bits/second, confusing name though right?)
[End of lecture on 1.4]
[Lecture on 2.2]

Both compression (aka source coding) and error correction (aka channel coding) deal with redundancy
Compression: Eliminate redundancy where possible
Error Correction: Introduce 'enough' redundancy

Software Engineering Textbook:

Software Engineering (Ian Sommerville) Pearson, 10th ed
Recommends not bothering with the Java one, you can learn Java from the slides or online, but the software engineering textbook is good.


Why Java?
Getting started
Hello World
Data Types
Operators
Strings
I/O
Control Flow
Arrays

Java White Paper:

Simple, Object-Oriented and Familiar
Robust & secure
Architecture neutral and portable
High performance
Interpreted, threaded, and dynamic
Faster development cycle, less compiling and shite
Constant garbage collection for good memory management
Multithreading is basked into Java programs
Maintains the OOP nature of C++ but more secure, robust, convenient

C/C++ is compiled to 'native code' which cannot be ported between machines
Java executable (.jar) runs on any machine via a virtual machine
Java compiles to 'bytecode' (.jar file)
Java is highly employable

Download and install the latest Java SDK. Easiest to use the installer.
Download and install IntelliJ (IDE)

/* Multiline comments like this @author Thomas O'Dea @version 1.0 09-09-2024 Those lines are 'JavaDoc' notation */ public class HelloWorld { public static void main(String[] args) { System.out.println("Hello, World"); // Print } } Copy

- Our main method gets String[] args from CLI

int (4 bytes)

char
double
boolean
Variables can be inferred implicitly, e.g.

enum types are useful:

Public vs Private fields
Classes can access private fields from other instances as long as its the same class
Static methods can be accessed without creating an instance
Use getter and setter methods, never interface directly with the fields - make fields private and getter/setter methods public

Declare what package your class is in at the beginning of the file: package com.hortsmann.corejava; import java.time.*; public class Employee { // more code here } Copy
Then import as a package in another import com.hortsmann.corejava.Employee; Copy

[Lecture on 3.1]


Concepts
Example: managers and employees
Polymorphism
Methods with variable number of parameters
Abstract classes
Enumeration classes

A class can inherit attributes from a 'parent' class
Example Every employee in your company has a salary, DOB, and PPSN. You might create an 'employee' class to store those. Only managers get 'bonuses' so you might create a Manager class, which inherits from Employee, and adds a 'bonus' attribute. public class Manager extends Employee { private double bonus; Manager(String name, double salary, int year) { super(name, salary, year); // Call the super class constructor! bonus = 0; } public double getSalary() { double baseSalary = super.getSalary(); return baseSalary + bonus; } public void setBonus(double b) { bonus = b; } } Copy
You can treat child classes as an instance of the parent class, e.g.
var staff = new Employee[3]; staff[0] = new Manager("Thomas O'Dea",80000,2000); staff[0].setBonus(1000); Copy

Code can be written that will run on objects of various different classes.
In the above example, calling getSalary() will call the Manager function, even if the array stores Employee objects.
See more at w3schools.


A 'final' class cannot have subclasses
public final class Executive extends Manager {...} Copy

A final method cannot be overridden
public final String getName() {...} Copy

You can cast an inherited object into an instance of the parent object
If you do, you can later cast back and it will retain values it had from the subclass before.

package multipleparameters; public class Max{ public static void main (String[] args) { double largest = max(1.0, 0.5, 1.5); } private static double max (double... values) { double largest = Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY; for (double v : values ) { if (v > largest) { largest = v; } } return largest; } } Copy

Abstract classes cannot be instantiated as an object, they only exist to inherit more classes from
Abstract methods are simply placeholders for methods that will be overwritten in the inheriting class.
Example
UCD has to track professors and students.
Create a 'person' class. Because everybody will either fall under 'professor' or 'student' class, 'person' should be an abstract class. public abstract class Person { public abstract String getDescription(); private String name; public Person(String name) { this.name = name; } public String getName() { return name; } } public class Student extends Person { private String major; public Student(String name, String major) { super(name); // we can only use the abstract class because we have extended it this.major = major; } // Overwrite the abstract method public String getDescription() { return "a student majoring in "+major; } } Copy
This is generally used for security purposes.

Enumeration actually creates a class
public enum Size {SMALL, MEDIUM, LARGE, EXTRA_LARGE} Copy
All enumerated types extend the abstract class Enum. They inherit methods:

toString() - returns name of the value as string
toValue() - converts string to enum'd value
values() - returns an array of all the enum'd elements
ordinal() - returns the position of the enum'd value in the original enum declaration
Example You can add your own methods to an 'enum' class enum Size { SMALL("S"), MEDIUM("M"), LARGE("L"), EXTRA_LARGE("XL"); private String abbreviation; Size (STring abbreviation) { this.abbreviation = abbreviation; } public String getAbbreviation() { return abbreviation; } } Copy

A class' interface is the class name, public constants, public fields, and public method signatures.
A method signature is the return value, method name, and parameter list.
A method may be able to support multiple classes if it supports both interfaces. Polymorphism.
Example Reverse Interface package reversible; interface Reversible { String getName(); void setName(String name); } public class Student implements Reversible { public void setName(String name) { // Define the function's behaviour here } } Copy
A class can use multiple interfaces

You could also implement this by making a superclass with the methods you want instead of an interface.
Generally interfaces are for identifying common functions across entities but with different implementations of that method.


The JDK provides some interfaces:

Comparable (method for comparing two objects)
Iterables (works for enhanced for loops)
Cloneable (can be .clone()'d)
Serializable (has a method to serialise into a byte stream and back)
Observable (for GUIs)
Example Array Sort
Write a program that sort an array of integers. Solution:
In the Arrays class, there is a sort method.
This uses the compareTo(T other) method, which should return a negative, zero, or positive int depending on the comparison
You tell the compiler that your class has a suitable compareTo() method by implementing the Comparable interface. The Comparable interface is just interface Comparable<T> { int compareTo(T o); } Copy
